<TEXT>
a former stockbroker who bilked his golf buddies 
and other associates of more than 2 million was sentenced monday 
to five years in prison after pleading guilty to federal mail fraud 
and other charges 
us district court judge edward harrington sentenced walter f 
curran a former stockbroker with dean witter reynolds inc to two 
concurrent fiveyear terms followed by five years probation for 
mail and bank fraud 
a condition of his probation is that curran reimburse his 
victims 
harrington called the crime deliberate and calculated fraud 
it was fraud of enormous proportions he said one of the 
predominant motivations was excess greed 
curran 47 who pleaded guilty to 13 counts of mail fraud and 
bank fraud told the court he understood the serious nature of his 
crime 
its been a very trying period for everyone concerned with 
this he said 
curran also pleaded guilty to one count of violating currency 
transaction reporting laws for which he received a 13month 
sentence to be served concurrently with the other sentences that 
charge was filed in new york after curran was found to be carrying 
132000 in cash when he was arrested at the canadian border last 
february 
as part of his sentence curran was ordered to pay more than 
260000 to the bank of boston corp for overdrawing money in a 
series of checking transactions 
curran was suspended from dean witter reynolds in february 1989 
when he was arrested in connection with the disappearance of 239 
million he had convinced friends and associates to invest in his 
personal account instead of with dean witter 
defense attorney robert cordy described the broker from 
wellesley as a decent and engaging man probably the most 
generous person i have ever met who became desperate when he 
could not fulfill promises he had made to his investors 
starting in april 1981 curran solicited money from eight 
people including two golfing companions as well as his accountant 
and his lawyer at the time cordy said 
cordy said curran promised them interest payments of 20 percent 
if they invested in a deferred compensation account in his name 
instead however over the eight years curran invested 36 million 
in the stock market and other ventures 
during that time the funds suffered ups and downs but when the 
market collapsed on black monday in october 1987 curran lost his 
investors money as well as much of his own cordy said 
he had tried everything from gambling to long shots cordy 
said eventually when everything came crashing down there was no 
way he could continue to juggle the balls and get the money back 
faced with huge losses curran fled to canada and when he 
disappeared his scheme came to light he surrendered to 
authorities in massena ny 
</TEXT>
