<TEXT>
the reinstatement of the african 
national congress has brought little joy or hope to south africas 
black townships and activists say it wont change the harsh lives 
of millions of poor blacks 
president fw de klerks announcement friday that the anc and 
other antigovernment groups no longer will be banned along with 
other reforms prompted few celebrations in the sprawling townships 
while many foreign leaders hailed de klerks pronouncements 
just a few thousand of the countrys 28 million blacks marched or 
celebrated in most cities 
while applauding de klerks call for talks to resolve south 
africas racial problems antiapartheid leaders said the 
concessions would change little in the short term 
they said black asian and mixedrace south africans want total 
equality and full democracy immediately with no special privileges 
for whites de klerk hopes to preserve at least some white power 
and little will change for most blacks the activists say 
most of us realized that the speech did not change a single 
bit of the political realities and the living realities of our 
people the rev allan boesak said in an interview 
boesak a mixedrace clergyman and prominent antiapartheid 
leader said the changes would not ease the plight of millions of 
blacks who live in shantytowns struggling to feed and clothe their 
families 
there is no reason to celebrate while most nonwhites still face 
chronic unemployment malnutrition and poor education and health 
facilities he said 
the realities of apartheid will take away what joy or 
gratitude the people may have he said 
de klerks speech prompted no major celebrations in soweto the 
main black township outside johannesburg with a population of 25 
million 
in cape town a few hundred people many of them children 
attended a township victory celebration 
boesak said nonwhites do not trust the government after years 
of repression and would have little faith in its statements until 
they see real change in their lives 
many apartheid laws enforcing the separation of the races 
remain in effect and power and privilege are still vested in the 
hands of the white minority 
its going to take 10 to 15 years to make south africa nice 
said a young anc activist taking part in a protest in cape town he 
spoke on condition of anonymity 
activists said the modest black turnout to celebrate de klerks 
speech also reflected a lack of political organization and 
widespread apathy among many blacks that must be changed 
celebrations last year to mark the release from prison of walter 
sisulu and other senior anc leaders failed to fill a 70000seat 
stadium in soweto 
too many of the people are afraid or do not care said a 
labor union official who also insisted on not being identified 
while de klerk promised to end apartheid legislation allowing 
segregation of public facilities government ministers ruled out 
scrapping other apartheid laws at this time 
laws segregating residential areas and requiring south africans 
to register by race will be retained for now the ministers say 
they say the government still strongly supports the right of ethnic 
groups to live separately 
de klerk has spoken out against the concept of black majority 
rule and said repeal of apartheid laws would have to be negotiated 
as part of an overall settlement 
when you see through this maze of excitement over the 
speech apartheid is still very much intact said eugene nyati 
a political analyst at the center of african studies 
antiapartheid leaders say de klerk and his national party 
remain committed to preserving a special status for whites that 
would give them an indefinite hold on power 
it is unlikely that the promised land of a nonracial 
democracy will be reached before at best the second half of this 
decade said sampie terreblanche an opposition democratic party 
analyst 
black labor leaders are playing down de klerks reforms noting 
that the government has not ended the 3yearold state of 
emergency which gives police wide powers to curb dissent 
the people are not satisfied said one union leader who 
refused to be identified 
de klerk said he wanted to end the state of emergency as soon as 
possible but gave no date 
the government must prove its sincerity with rapid and massive 
change to end whiteminority rule and ease the plight of millions 
of poor blacks boesak said 
said the clergyman if mr de klerk really wants to give 
meaning to what he has said to give some meaning and direction 
to the grand vision he has painted he has to move very very 
quickly 
</TEXT>
