<DOCNO> AP900206-0003 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a study of domestic violence in milwaukee 
concluded that police cannot rely on past abuse incidents to 
predict and prevent homicides in which a husband or wife kills a 
spouse 
the study conducted by the washingtonbased crime control 
institute found that previous domestic violence was reported in 
only one of 33 adult domestic homicides in milwaukee during a 
22month period from 1987 to 1989 
the study challenges previous research suggesting that most 
domestic homicides are foretold by domestic violence calls said 
lawrence w sherman director of the study for the crime control 
institute 
police chief phillip areola said the findings were unexpected 
and disappointing and would set back police efforts to improve 
the prevention of spouse killings 
police have long hoped for a reliable basis for predicting and 
preventing domestic homicide areola said unfortunately the 
crime control institute research suggests we have not developed the 
tools to do that particular job 
the study released sunday found a group of 1112 couples had an 
average of more than three incidents of violence per couple during 
the 22month study period but none resulted in homicide 
in contrast only one of the 33 domestic homicide cases involved 
a couple with a previous report of violence 
millions of dollars have been paid out by taxpayers and 
insurers in lawsuits all based on the theory that police can 
predict and prevent domestic homicide sherman said according 
to the milwaukee evidence that theory is wrong 
its almost a suggestion that homicide and assault are two 
different phenomenons sherman added 
joseph weis a sociology professor and director of the center 
for law and justice at the university of washington said he isnt 
surprised by the studys findings 
we arent really very good at predicting any kind of crime on 
a regular basis weis said we cant tell you whether john or 
joe or jane will kill their spouse even if there is a history 
of violence 
but carey tradewell executive director of the milwaukee womens 
center said people who work with domestic violence cases do see a 
pattern 
what we see is that the longer women and men stay in a 
relationship where theres violence without any intervention there 
is repeated violence and the violence is more severe 
sherman said his data shows no evidence to support tradewells 
observation 
the findings contradict an earlier study conducted by the kansas 
city police department which found that 90 percent of domestic 
homicides had been preceded by a disturbance call at the address of 
either the victim or the offender in a twoyear period before the 
homicide 
the study will be published later this year by the academy of 
criminal justice sciences and the anderson publishing co of 
cincinnati in a book titled redefining crime responses to woman 
battering 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

