<TEXT>
chippewa indians seeking unlimited access 
to about 18 million acres of forest should be free to harvest 
timber without government regulation under 19thcentury treaties a 
chippewa lawyer told a federal judge monday 
lawyers for several northern wisconsin counties asked us 
district judge barbara crabb to allow government regulation of the 
indians activities to preserve timber resources 
david siegler who represents the chippewas bad river band 
said on the opening day of a trial to decide the matter that the 
chippewa do not believe all timber regulations issued by counties 
are necessary to avoid deterioration of the forest land at stake in 
the case 
siegler also told the judge the chippewa believe the land 
belongs to them 
the forests involved in the case are managed by counties which 
make about 3 million annually from timber sales 
it doesnt make sense to make the indians pay for something 
that is theirs siegler said 
wisconsins six chippewa bands retain the right to hunt fish 
gather food and cut timber under courtaffirmed treaties that ceded 
northern wisconsin to the federal government 
federal courts have upheld the treaties in rulings dating to 
1983 in the case initiated by the chippewa the previous court 
rulings left it up to ms crabb to decide how the land should be 
managed 
several other issues relating to the treaties including deer 
and bear hunting are still pending others such as tribal fishing 
and wild rice gathering have been settled 
we will prove that our regulations are necessary for 
preserving the timber resources of northern wisconsin counties 
attorney thomas mcnulty who represents the counties told the 
judge 
the trial is expected to last several weeks 
about eight counties are involved in the timber case though 28 
counties will be affected by the outcome 
assistant attorney general lisa levin said the state does not 
plan to charge the indians a user fee but seeks a ruling on 
whether the indians could hire nonindians to work for their timber 
harvest operations 
she said the indians want to expand the scope of the treaty 
rights to nonindians 
crabb must decide to what degree county state and federal 
governments can regulate the chippewas timber cutting in forests 
also used by the paper industry in wisconsin 
tribal lawyers have argued the treaties allow the chippewa 
unlimited access to cut timber without the regulations or user fees 
imposed on nonindian loggers and that they should have first 
access to all the timber they can cut in county and statemanaged 
forests 
county officials claim the forests might be destroyed if user 
fees are waived for the indians since the money is used to replant 
trees and care for the land 
were just saying that the indians should abide by the same 
regulations as everyone else said loren sloan of the wisconsin 
counties forest association 
if they dont pay to protect our forests the taxpayers are 
going to have to pay for the indians to come in and harvest timber 
for free sloan said 
forest products manufacturers employ about 77000 people and 
produce about 8 billion worth of products annually in wisconsin 
overall the state department of development reported 
unemployment rates on most of the six chippewa reservations in 
wisconsin exceed 50 percent and indians are looking to logging as a 
way to boost their economies siegler said 
</TEXT>
