<TEXT>
the search for the next great verdi soprano 
resumed at the metropolitan opera as susan dunn a rising young 
american star made her debut in il trovatore 
she may not yet be the answer to an opera lovers prayers but 
on the strength of her performance monday night the arkansas 
native is a force to be reckoned with for some time to come 
in the grueling role of leonora dunn displayed a voice of 
considerable power beauty and agility and yet she made a 
curiously muted impression never quite throwing herself into the 
frenzy of the occasion when verdi demanded it perhaps it was the 
difficulty she was having in her upper register where some high 
notes seemed forced and one or two were omitted entirely 
even with that qualification for sheer vocal luster she has the 
edge over aprile millo another young american who has been laying 
claim to the heavy verdi roles once owned by the likes of leontyne 
price and zinka milanov another aspirant alessandra marc made a 
debut earlier this season in aida showing phenomenal potential 
and a lot of unresolved vocal problems 
dunns was not the only debut of note monday night as the 
villainous count di luna paolo gavanelli a young italian 
baritone made an unscheduled debut replacing the hungarian lajos 
miller who had fallen ill gavanelli made a strong impression his 
mediumsize voice brimming with vigor 
the conductor also was new to the met rico saccani from 
arizona not italy as the name might suggest led a peppy and 
idiomatic performance 
it may sound like a bonus but it wasnt that the met presented 
not one but two tenors in the part of manrico ermanno mauro begged 
off halfway through complaining of tracheitis franco bonanome 
who took over sounded as if he might be headed for his sick bed as 
well by the time the night was out 
the finest singer on stage was mezzo dolora zajick a powerhouse 
who did full justice to the juicy role of the mad gypsy azucena 
whether singing softly or soaring above the orchestra she was 
thrilling 
