<TEXT>
a woman filed a 20 million negligence 
lawsuit monday against a japanese manufacturer of ltryptophan a 
dietary supplement linked to a rare and potentially fatal blood 
disorder 
helen jones 52 of portland claimed in the lawsuit filed in 
multnomah county circuit court that the showa denko company was 
negligent in manufacturing ltryptophan leading her to suffer 
eosinophilia myalgia syndrome 
the rare disease is characterized by abnormal levels of 
eosinophils a type of white blood cell victims complain of severe 
muscle pain weakness and fatigue swelling in the arms legs and 
face fevers rashes and in some cases breathing disorders 
ltryptophan is an amino acid that has been sold over the 
counter as a nutritional supplement and a sleep aid for decades 
without harmful effects 
imports of ltryptophan were halted in december after the number 
of eosinophilia myalgia syndrome cases began mounting 
by the end of january nearly 1200 cases of the disease had 
been reported nationally with at least a dozen deaths attributed 
to it according to officials with the national centers for disease 
control 
jones said in her lawsuit that showa denko has refused to 
cooperate with us health authorities displaying callous 
disregard for the rights and health of plaintiff and all the other 
victims of ltryptophan in oregon and elsewhere in the united 
states 
jones a forklift driver claimed in her lawsuit that her health 
is worsening and that other victims of the syndrome also suffer 
deteriorating health 
dr david fleming deputy state epidemiologist said in december 
that the condition of many eosinophilia myalgia syndrome victims 
did not improve quickly after they stopped taking the dietary 
supplement containing ltryptophan 
cdc doctors in atlanta say there is no effective treatment for 
eosinophilia myalgia syndrome and they have nearly ruled out the 
possibility that some unknown ingredient contaminated capsules or 
pills containing ltryptophan 
dr edwin m kilbourne who is leading the cdc investigation 
has said ltryptophan itself might be causing the disease although 
ltryptophan manufactured by other companies apparently has not 
triggered it 
jones attorney gayle troutwine said showa denko is the 
sixthlargest petrochemical manufacturer in japan with profits of 
nearly 12 billion last year 
</TEXT>
