jury selection began monday in a trial 
pitting two families in a dispute over profits and ownership of 
guess the countrys topselling jeans maker 
the 12member superior court panel will decide whether to award 
damages to the marciano family which founded guess in 1981 and 
sold a half interest of the company in 1983 to the nakash family 
which also own jordache jeans 
in the first part of the twostage trial a jury last year found 
the nakashes intended to steal for jordache trendy guess clothing 
designs 
the marcianos now are seeking more than 500 million in damages 
plus a return of the nakashes half ownership of guess judge 
norman epstein will decide whether the nakashes must relinquish 
their interest 
also at issue is disposition of a frozen account containing the 
nakashes accrued share of guess profits that contains more than 
93 million 
opening statements were expected feb 13 
the four frenchborn marciano brothers maurice armand paul 
and georges also contend that the israeliborn nakashes joe 
ralph and avi were responsible for destroying a guess fashion 
subsidiary gasoline 
the marcianos also named as defendants a hong kong couple lee 
sec mon and his wife who manufactured jordache products in the 
british crown colony they allege the lees were to have 
manufactured gasoline designs but diverted materials to jordache 
the lees are unlikely to appear at trial because of an 
outstanding warrant for their arrest on customs violations 
involving garment imports according to a source close to the case 
who spoke on condition of anonymity 
founded on an investment of 170000 guess last year sold 500 
