<TEXT>
the energy department says virtually all its 
nuclear weapons plants appear to be violating safety health and 
environmental rules and the department itself is to blame for 
failing to correct the problems 
a report released by the department monday said some of the 
health and safety violations posed relatively high risks of 
injury or death to small numbers of workers at the plants among 
the problems cited was improper use of toxic substances and 
electrical dangers 
the report compiled previously disclosed problems at six weapons 
plants the rocky flats plutonium processing plant in colorado the 
fernald uranium processing plant and the mound weapons laboratory 
in ohio the y12 uranium plant in tennessee the pantex weapons 
assembly plant in texas and the west valley radioactive waste site 
in new york 
the report was prepared by the department to analyze the 
findings of special investigations of the six plants by private 
contractors and consultants the rest of the weapons plants are to 
be investigated during 1990 
energy secretary james d watkins expressed dismay at the 
conclusions including a finding that five of six weapons plants 
evaluated last fall were storing wastes in violation of federal 
environmental laws and three were inadequately controlling 
radiation 
the report said other common problems include poor emergency 
planning a failure by plant managers to take environmental 
regulations seriously and a shortage of skilled workers 
the report blamed the problems partly on the energy departments 
failure to impose tougher management practices at the plants which 
are owned by the government but run by private contractors 
we must demonstrate that we are able to discipline ourselves 
and our contractors watkins wrote in an internal memorandum 
released with the report our inability to conform to our own 
requirements is particularly disturbing 
one of the plants cited as illegally storing wastes was rocky 
flats which is under fbi investigation for possible criminal 
violations of environmental laws watkins has acknowledged before 
that rocky flats and other atomic bomb plants are not complying 
with waste laws and has pledged to correct the problems as quickly 
as possible 
in his memorandum to department employees watkins said that 
although he saw indications of improvements at the plants he was 
not satisfied that all managers take the need for further 
improvements seriously 
steps to eliminate the business as usual approach to 
compliance are still required he wrote 
