the battle to restore the death penalty in 
new york again may rest on a conservative republican senator whose 
bout with cancer has given him second thoughts about bringing back 
the electric chair 
sen james donovan missed mondays vote in the state senate on 
legislation to restore capital punishment a measure democratic 
gov mario cuomo has promised to veto for the eighth straight year 
a consistent death penalty supporter donovan was unable to vote 
because he was suffering the side effects of chemotherapy said 
edward byrne an aide to the 25year senate veteran the 
legislation was approved 4020 
the measure now goes to the 150member assembly where a vote 
isnt expected until late february at the earliest 
without donovans vote or a switch by one of the no votes 
death penalty advocates lack the 41 senate votes needed to override 
a veto 
thirtyseven states have death penalty laws new york is the 
largest state without one 
the states last execution was in 1963 
last year donovan said his battle with cancer had caused him to 
have second thoughts about the death penalty that was enough to 
prompt the senates republican leadership to scrap any attempt at 
an override in 1989 
