<TEXT>
the food and drug administration says tests 
for antibiotics in milk samples from 14 metropolitan areas show the 
nations milk supply is safe 
the fda said its findings contradict the results of screenings 
by the wall street journal and the center for science in the public 
interest which recently found residues of potentially harmful 
drugs used to treat sick cattle 
our study indicates that the american dairy farmer is using 
animal drugs carefully and conscientiously and that the milk 
supply does not contain unsafe drug residues gerald guest 
director of fdas center for veterinary medicine said in a 
statement monday 
the journals tests conducted by rutgers university scientists 
on 50 retail samples collected in 10 major cities found 38 percent 
were contaminated with antibiotics and sulfa drugs used to treat 
sick cattle this class of drugs includes sulfamethazine a 
suspected carcinogen 
the survey by the center for science in the public interest 
conducted in conjunction with the journal tested 20 milk samples 
from store shelves in metropolitan washington and found 20 percent 
were tainted 
the fda noted at the time the tests used in the screenings 
known as charm ii can detect only classes of drugs not specific 
drugs within a class it also said the levels of residues found in 
the journals testing did not pose a public health threat 
the fda also used the charm ii method in its tests and got 
positive readings for 51 percent of its 70 samples 
however the fda said it also used new testing methods that are 
more sensitive and specific than charm ii none of the charm ii 
positives was confirmed by the new methods the fda said also 
testing for specific drugs found no contamination with 
sulfamethazine which is not approved for use in any foodproducing 
animal 
the fda samples were taken from atlanta baltimore boston 
chicago dallas denver kansas city los angeles miami 
minneapolisst paul philadelphia new york san francisco and 
seattle 
michael jacobson executive director of the center for science 
in the public interest said the charm ii test is well documented 
and reliable 
its puzzling that the fda would not be able to confirm any 
samples that charm ii found contaminants in he said i think 
the reason for the discrepancy has to be determined before one can 
say anything definite 
the fda said it plans to regularly monitor pasteurized milk for 
the presence of drug residues to supplement testing by the states 
the agency also said it will work toward adoption by the states 
of new testing procedures states currently rely on a method 
originally designed to detect penicillin and which also detects 
other antibiotics but not with the same sensitivity 
