<DOCNO> AP900206-0075 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the 550 million gamma ray 
observatory arrived aboard a giant cargo plane today for liftoff 
next year on a mission to help scientists unlock the secrets of the 
universe from high above the earth 
the 17ton observatory was trucked from trw inc in redondo 
beach calif which built the satellite to los angeles 
international airport on monday it was flown aboard an air force 
c5a to the kennedy space center 
it is scheduled to be placed in earth orbit in november by space 
shuttle atlantis and will be the heaviest spacecraft ever deployed 
by a shuttle said trw spokeswoman montye male 
the gamma ray observatory is the second of the national 
aeronautics and space administrations great observatories which 
the agency says will help scientists understand the birth and 
structure of the universe and the origin and evolution of stars 
planets and life 
the first great observatory is the hubble space telescope which 
is scheduled to be launched from space shuttle discovery in april 
the others are the advanced xray astrophysics facility which is 
to be launched from a shuttle in 1997 and the space infrared 
telescope facility scheduled for launch from a rocket in 1999 
each of the observatories will detect a different form of 
electromagnetic radiation visible light gamma rays xrays and 
infrared light which is heat 
the hubble is an incredibly powerful optical telescope that will 
look back almost to the beginning of time to study light from stars 
and galaxies 
the gamma ray observatory will be equipped with four detectors 
to spend two to eight or more years studying gamma rays emitted by 
various processes in space including the big bang which is 
the gargantuan explosion scientists believe created the universe 
about 15 billion years ago 
gamma rays are called the messengers of creation because when 
the big bang started everything off gamma rays were emitted 
male said she said the observatory will conduct a comprehensive 
scientific effort to learn more about the origin and fate of the 
universe 
through the gros instruments humankind may be able to 
witness the birth of elements the death of stars and discover 
clues about quasars pulsars and black holes she said 
most of the elements that make up earth and all living things 
were created by the death of stars in fiery supernova explosions 
pulsars and black holes are the incredibly dense remnants of 
supernovas quasars or quasistellar objects are mysterious 
sources of vast amounts of light and other energy 
the observatory is now 15by30by15 feet but once its solar 
