the united nationssponsored conference of technical experts is 
meeting to work on a proposed treaty to deal with global warming 
reilly issued a statement saying the presidents remarks made 
clear his determination to lead the world in addressing global 
climate change 
bush does not believe it is time for a call to arms on 
global warming but instead favors continued research presidential 
spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters after the presidents 
remarks 
but many environmentalists argue there is enough scientific 
evidence to warrant a commitment from the united states and other 
industrial nations to reduce global warming gases especially 
carbon dioxide from the burning of fossil fuels 
scientists fear such an accumulation of manmade pollutants will 
act like a greenhouse trapping heat and reflecting it back to 
earth causing a warming of the globe scientists disagree on how 
severe the warming will become or its effect although some 
scientists predict droughts in some interior regions and coastal 
flooding because of higher ocean levels 
reducing greenhouse gases would require less reliance on coal 
oil and natural gas and would require industry to develop more 
energyefficient automobiles and industrial plants which industry 
fears could result in widespread economic disruption 
