<TEXT>
the terrapin is a gourmet delicacy and key 
soup ingredient to some a noble creature and wonderful pet to 
others but to state environmental officials its a threatened 
species that needs protection 
the turtles salt water habitat is imperiled by development and 
its ranks are declining because of its regained popularity on some 
dinner tables 
the state department of environmental conservation recently 
issued regulations setting up a terrapin harvest or hunting 
season for diamondback terrapin 
under the regulations wouldbe terrapin hunters must buy state 
licenses and terrapin capturing is forbidden during the turtles 
nesting period in may june and july the regulations also set 
minimum and maximum size limits on captured terrapin 
we think that because of loss of habitat and loss of nesting 
areas in addition to a continued desire to eat them primarily 
with the ethnic groups and gourmet restaurants its survival could 
become a problem again said alvin breisch a state wildlife 
biologist 
this isnt the first time the turtles have been threatened by 
their own good taste said breisch 
they were completely wiped out in many locations in the early 
1900s said breisch the food fad kind of died off about the 
same time the turtles died off but theyve been slowly coming 
back 
in new york state the terrapins are found only in the brackish 
salty water off long island and at the mouth of the hudson river 
the dec doesnt keep a terrapin tally breisch said 
we dont know how many there are but theyre certainly not as 
numerous as they were 100 years ago he said 
jim vanabbema can see evidence of a decline just by going to a 
fish market hes a member of the new york state turtle and 
tortoise society which petitioned the dec to regulate terrapin 
capture 
many of our members had been alarmed by the quantity of 
diamondback terrapin that were sold in chinatown and other fish 
markets across the city said vanabbema editor of the 
20yearold societys newsletter plastron papers the plastron is 
a turtles bottom shell 
theyre not very big turtles seldom growing to more than 9 
inches long their scutes the individual pieces that make up 
their shells have very elaborate concentric patterns a 
distinctive mark on a terrapins face makes it look like it has 
white lips breisch said 
if you see the turtle it basks in the open water rather than 
crawling up on logs or sitting on the beach it basks just by 
floating on the surface and it sticks its head up and youll see 
the w hite lips if you see that youll know its a terrapin he 
said 
terrapins are not aggressive make good pets and can live 30 or 
40 years said vanabbema 
some of the turtle societys 1000 members are also concerned 
about the conditions in which the turtles are kept after capture 
said vanabbema who owns 18 turtles and a parrot 
they are kept at best in a dry tank maybe two or three layers 
deep sometimes even worse he said they are often in a 
diseased state they are in very poor health because of the 
extreme stress of being without food or water for weeks or longer 
the fact that turtles must be butchered shortly before cooking 
should contribute to their continued existence said breisch 
whoever buys them has to take them home and kill them and 
clean them said breisch turtle meat doesnt last very long 
after its been killed just like lobster meat 
i think that discourages a lot of people they actually 
wouldnt want to kill it themselves 
