charge the defense contends reagan would have corroborated norths 
assertion that the president and his top advisers decided that in 
order to protect the lives of us hostages held in lebanon they 
wouldnt disclose us involvement with the november 1985 hawk 
shipment 
but irancontra prosecutors say north was unable to identify a 
single instance where reagan directly told him to obstruct congress 
on another point norths attorney asked the appeals court to 
overturn the former presidential aides conviction because of the 
pervasive dissemination of his congressional testimony 
witnesses jurors prosecutors and grand jurors could not avoid 
exposure to testimony north gave a congressional committee 
investigating the irancontra affair simon said 
north was granted immunity from prosecution for his 
congressional testimony prosecutors said they had not read or seen 
any of that testimony and had gathered their own evidence the 
congressional testimony was carried on live television and reported 
widely throughout the media 
in light of the pervasive dissemination there are no 
procedures that could ensure a fair trial simon argued 
he said grand jurors hearing testimony that resulted in 
indictments against north were not instructed to avoid reading 
newspapers or watching television instead he said the 
governments special prosecutor told the grand jurors to avoid 
tainted material or news that related to north 
they were told they could watch but if it came to tainted 
material then skip over it said simon you could read but 
when you get to an article that is tainted skip over 
he said the special prosecutor chose convenience instead of 
absolutely forbidding the grand jurors from reading newspapers or 
watching television 
the publicity was absolutely pervasive he said this 
grand jury was not shielded 
lynch the governments attorney responded that norths lawyers 
are equatingexposure with taint he called it overreaching 
of what the law requires 
the obstruction charge involved a 1985 shipment of hawk missiles 
to iran while the documents that were destroyed showed norths 
assistance to the nicaraguan contras the gratuity was a 13800 
home security system which north accepted from richard secord who 
north enlisted to run supplies to the rebels fighting the 
nicaraguan government 
gesell on july 5 placed north on probation for two years fined 
him 150000 and sentenced him to 1200 hours of community service 
north is performing the community service while appealing the 
convictions and fine 
