a judge today dismissed a legal challenge 
by mcdonalds restaurants and others to portlands new ban on food 
containers made of polystyrene foam 
the law which took effect jan 1 prohibits the use of the 
packaging by restaurants and food vendors it was not being 
enforced pending resolution of the legal challenge 
circuit judge douglas r spencer heard arguments monday on 
whether to dismiss the lawsuit and granted the request this 
morning he ruled that the city was within its authority in 
enacting the ban 
the lawsuit filed by three recycling companies and several 
restaurants including mcdonalds franchises claimed the ban 
violates state solidwaste law and policies mcdonalds uses foam 
in packaging big macs and other items 
but city attorney jeffrey l rogers argued that state policies 
on solidwaste management dont prohibit the city from banning 
foam the city contends foam food containers fill up landfills 
take generations to break down and are not recyclable 
mark l cushing representing the plaintiffs contended that the 
ban conflicts with state priorities for waste management he said a 
trial would prove that polystyrene foam is recyclable and his 
clients are recycling it 
mcdonalds and other foam users have argued that the alternative 
to foam is paper products which would end up at a landfill the 
last alternative on the state priority list 
