<TEXT>
west germanys labor chief on 
tuesday urged east germans to think twice before emigrating to the 
west because of the already overcrowded job market 
the continuing flood of east germans resettling in west germany 
has raised enormous concerns in both countries leading to warnings 
of serious economic and social problems 
federal officials say that so far this year 66000 east germans 
have emigrated to west germany an alarming average of nearly 
1800 per day arriving in one of europes most densely populated 
countries 
heinrich franke the head of west germanys federal labor 
office said 132100 east germans were registered as unemployed 
last month 
i appeal to all potential resettlers to consider their future 
job and housing possibilities before leaving the german democratic 
republic franke said in nuremberg 
whoever plans to resettle should not simply give up their old 
job and apartment and head off to the west by car he added 
as an added service to east germans franke said government 
employment offices near the border and in west berlin were 
counseling potential immigrants on their chances 
job opportunities vary widely for the newcomers 
east german craftsmen and bakers for example often take jobs 
that many young west germans snub 
but newly arrived physicians are finding a market so overcrowded 
that many have proposed sending doctors to east germany as a 
humanitarian gesture and as a way to keep the medical personnel 
busy 
franke added that east german factory workers and engineers were 
also having a difficult time finding work in west germany 
the overall west german unemployment rate climbed to 85 percent 
in january from 8 percent in december franke announced that meant 
that nearly 22 million workers were jobless in west germany 
west germany also has been coping with an influx of tens of 
thousands of ethnic germans from other parts of eastern europe 
including poland romania and the soviet union 
they accounted for 137500 jobless workers in addition to those 
from east germany franke said 
the influx straining the job market and the housing market has 
led to growing calls for curbs including appeals from saarland 
state governor oskar lafontaine 
lafontaine virtually certain to be the opposition social 
democrats chancellor candidate this year has said the country 
cannot maintain its opendoor policy indefinitely 
the social democrats economics expert wolfgang roth predicts 
the influx of east germans could jump even further in the coming 
weeks 
we have the impression that about 3 million gdr citizens east 
