<TEXT>
the library at the national press club will 
continue to bear the name of journalist hl mencken despite what 
the clubs secretary described as despicable remarks about jews 
and blacks in menckens recently published diaries 
the clubs board of governors voted 74 monday to retain 
menckens name after receiving appeals from notables including 
historian arthur m schlesinger jr who urged the club not to 
rename its library in an excess of selfrighteousness 
mick rood a reporter for the states news service and the clubs 
secretary argued for removing menckens name saying his remarks 
about jews and blacks were despicable 
in all his years of running down say the methodists the 
context was ideological a hardedged social commentary rood 
said whenever he excoriated the philistines he presented a body 
of convincing evidence the only evidence behind his antisemitic 
remarks was venom 
this club neednt honor this man in this way rood said 
we can admire but we neednt revere 
schlesinger in a letter to the club said mencken had his 
faults like all the rest of us and he made his mistakes some of 
them awful but he was a great newspaperman and basically a 
liberating influence on american society i hope the national 
press club will not turn its back on him in an excess of 
selfrighteousness 
economist john kenneth galbraith and journalist lawrence e 
spivak also wrote to the board urging that the mencken name be 
retained 
his comments on jews and blacks are no worse than those one 
could have heard around harvard or any other major university in 
those days and without evident shock galbraith said you are 
not i trust expelling ivy league graduates of that period to the 
extent that they survive 
spivak who succeeded mencken as editor of the american mercury 
magazine and later moderated meet the press on nbc radio and 
television wrote mencken was a great journalist but like many 
of us was stupid about a lot of things actually his attitude 
toward jews was like that of many selfsatisfied jews that he knew 
because they were jewish they felt they could say whatever they 
wanted about other jews without being considered antisemitic 
morton c paulson associate editor of changing times magazine 
told his fellow board members 
i am convinced that he was far from being a racist a bigot or 
sympathetic to the third reich 
the last column he wrote for the baltimore evening sun before 
he suffered a disabling stroke was a withering attack on the city 
for segregating a public park 
in any event he added nothing will change the fact that 
his contributions to journalism were extraordinary and he was one 
of the greatest literary scholars of all times 
the library was named the hl mencken library and reference 
center when it opened in 1984 in naming it the board noted that 
mencken once said he could be the the second best expert on any 
subject if he had a firstclass library behind him 
mencken who died in 1956 was a longtime columnist for the 
evening sun in baltimore as well as the author of a highly praised 
work on the american language and a classic memoir 
his recently published diaries contain such phrases as a brisk 
clever jew and a highly dubious jew and he says of 
colored women that they are all essentially childlike and 
even hard experience does not teach them anything 
the motion defeated by the board would have removed menckens 
name and left the renaming of the library to future action 
those voting against the motion and thus to keep the mencken 
