<TEXT>
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter sent 
congress new farm proposals on tuesday that he said maintain the 
federalbenefit principles of the expiring 1985 law but give 
farmers more flexibility 
he did not however offer any advice for financing the 
proposals saying well have to legislate in cooperation with 
congress 
we dont intend to make specific recommendations on how to 
meet budget requirements he said 
the budget proposals president bush released last week call for 
a cut in fiscal 1991 commodity spending of 15 billion 
when asked specifically about those cuts yeutter said this 
document doesnt deal with budget it deals with policy 
he said the proposals generally are modifications to the 1985 
farm act designed to provide the flexibility to adjust to changes 
in the international marketplace maintain the successful course 
set in the 1985 legislation and balance the need for an 
abundant safe and affordable food supply with conservation and 
improvement of our environment 
to give farmers the planting flexibility yeutter said they 
consider the most important part of any new legislation he has 
proposed a normal crop acreage concept 
this would allow farmers to plant crops based on market demand 
without loss of farm program benefits 
it would define crops that could be substituted for program 
crops authorize cropspecific acreage reduction programs and 
provide authority to plant on idled acres in exchange for giving up 
specified deficiency payments 
the administration proposals follow the introduction monday by 
the house agriculture committee of its 1990 farm bill 
after a glance at yeutters recommendations the house 
agriculture committee chairman rep kika de la garza dtexas 
said he thought congress would come up with legislation acceptable 
to the white house without much trouble 
the senate agriculture committee chairman sen patrick leahy 
responded negatively to yeutters proposal 
unfortunately the heart of the farm bill is not there said 
leahy a vermont democrat the administration fails to tell 
farmers what it thinks target prices should be 
american farmers dont know what their income will be and 
congress does not know how much the administration will be willing 
to spend on farm programs 
a spokeswoman for the national farmers union cheryl cook said 
her biggest criticism of the proposal was the lack of any 
information whatsover on price levels relating to commodity 
supports and targets 
for our money the whole purpose of the pricesupport program 
is income protection for farmers and that seems to be the one area 
that the administration has chosen not to look at at all 
questioned about farm income at a news conference yeutter said 
i see no reason why we should not be able to provide net farm 
income that would give a very satisfactory standard of living to 
farmers even though the federal contribution will decline 
he also said that the effect of his proposals on consumer prices 
would be nominal 
the administrations recommendation that crop insurance be 
replaced with a new crop disaster resistance program has already 
been floated in congress and is likely to produce lively debate 
during discussion of the farm bill 
the federal crop insurance corp which provides subsidized 
allrisk coverage to farmers has been losing money for many years 
with many farmers spurning the insurance and relying on congress to 
bail them out when an emergency arises 
we have not found a way to make crop insurance work within 
realistic budget targets said the secretary 
he said his proposal would provide payments for individual 
losses whenever countywide harvested yields fall below 65 percent 
of normal on a cropbycrop basis 
he envisions a standing law designed along the lines of the ad 
hoc disaster legislation passed in 1988 and 1989 to provide farmers 
drought relief his proposal would eliminate the need for such ad 
hoc bills he said 
other highlights in yeutters recommendations include 
a grain reserve and stocks policy based on annual contracts 
that give the farmer more say in deciding when stocks should be 
released into the marketplace 
changing the trigger for acreagereduction programs to be more 
consistent with market and farmer needs 
extending the loan rate formula for wheat and feedgrains to 
upland cotton extra longstaple cotton and rice the 1985 loan rate 
formula for soybeans also would be extended 
incentives to use perennial cover crops on setaside acreage as 
a means to naturally improve soil fertility 
methods for cutting down fraud in the use of food stamps and 
grants to organizations that test innovative ways to get food 
stamps to the homeless 
tightening of the farmers home administration programs so 
borrowers cant so easily abuse its loan policy 
requiring all exported corn to be tested for aflatoxin 
</TEXT>
