the army said tuesday it has begun punishing 
palestinians who hurl rocks at israelis by sealing off their houses 
or blocking off individual rooms 
the policy which could affect hundreds of families in the 
occupied west bank and gaza strip drew immediate criticism from 
civil rights groups and liberal politicians who said the measure 
amounts to collective punishment 
also tuesday two israeli civilians shot and killed a 
palestinian who stoned their truck and 33 other palestinians were 
wounded in clashes with israeli troops the army and arab reports 
said 
col ahaz benari the armys legal adviser for the west bank 
said the new penalty was necessary because of the danger of 
stonethrowing the main tactic of the nearly 26monthold 
palestinian uprising against israeli rule 
because this phenomenon is still deeply rooted and lately to 
our great regret is on an increase it was decided to widen this 
sanction for this phenomenon in an attempt to quell it benari 
said 
since the arab uprising broke out in december 1987 the army has 
destroyed or sealed at least 395 homes to punish arabs suspected of 
firebomb or other serious attacks but the penalty was not usually 
used for rockthrowing 
the army generally seals rooms or whole houses by blocking the 
doors and windows with concrete blocks or bricks and cement 
sometimes the family is told to do the labor at times the army 
has welded metal doors or shutters shut 
the first sealings under the new policy occurred overnight in 
the west bank the army said several rooms of a house in nablus 
were blocked off because one family member threw a rock through a 
cars windshield injuring the israeli driver 
in the town of qalqilya several rooms were sealed off in the 
home of a palestinian charged with wounding a border policeman with 
a stone 
the families were allowed to remain in one room of each house 
the army said it did not say how many members there were in each 
family 
