<TEXT>
artists professors and veterans of the 
free speech movement on tuesday unveiled finalists in a contest to 
commemorate the protest that was the forerunner of a decade of 
dissent 
the proposals for the monument to be built with private 
donations and given to the university of california at berkeley 
include a metal soap box a suspended electronic billboard 
broadcasting computer messages from around the world giant cracks 
in a plaza bricks inscribed with speeches and an autonomous 
nation within a 6inch circle 
the idea of freedom of speech and action should be 
memorialized and done so in the place where it all started said 
peter selz former chief curator of the museum of modern art in new 
york and a project organizer 
the sculpture to be commissioned with 70000 has revived a 
bitter debate over the movements legacy at berkeley which sparked 
four months of demonstrations in 1964 after the school banned 
political activities on campus 
student tactics including sitins humorous music fetes and an 
alternative press became the model for the 10 years of civil 
rights and antiwar demonstrations that followed 
chancellor ira michael heyman suggested that he may refuse the 
artwork saying hes unsure the movement deserves an honor 
in his only public comment on the proposal he wrote in a letter 
to project organizers that those involved in the movement were 
not very good at designing public art to commemorate their own 
actions 
journalism professor david littlejohn derided it as a tribute to 
the unjustified selfassurance of the campus liberal elite 
which he characterizes as ironically intolerant of divergent views 
the free speech movement began oct 1 1964 when student mario 
savio and friend jack weinberg began distributing political 
material on the universitys sproul plaza 
weinberg was arrested and placed in the back of a patrol car 
but hundreds of students surrounded the automobile and for 32 hours 
refused to let 600 police officers take him into custody 
photographs of savio and others addressing the crowd from atop 
the car were published around the world leading to sympathetic 
student strikes until the university dropped its ban several months 
later 
the protests culminated in a december sitin at sproul hall 
where 773 people were taken into custody then the largest mass 
arrest in california history 
i feel theres a lot of pride among students today in the 
students who were here before us said matthew miller an 
architecture student and a member of the committee that selected 
the finalists from 277 applications 
the proposals will be displayed at the university art museum 
through march 3 after which the committee and project organizers 
will announce the winner the public can register their favorite 
with ballots 
at a tuesday news conference committee members including 
internationally known artists said the proposals would be refined 
and possibly modified they reserved the right to combine several 
of the ideas 
charles schwartz a physics professor since 1960 devised the 
idea of the monument last year after finding a recently installed 
campus statue of two black bears which he labeled big fat 
powerful complacent representative of the worst of california 
since then the proposal has receieved support from 100 
professors politicians students and most of the leaders of the 
free speech movement 
</TEXT>
