prime minister margaret thatcher said thursday a 
ban on new investment in south africa should be lifted when 
president fw de klerks government frees imprisoned black leader 
nelson mandela 
she said reforms de klerk announced friday had been welcomed 
internationally and as we agreed both at the last meeting of the 
european community and in the commonwealth it is necessary to have 
encouragement for such steps as well as chastisement for what has 
not yet been done 
we do believe that when mr mandela is released it would be 
advisable to release some of the very minor sanctions in 
particular the voluntary ban on new investment mrs thatcher 
said in the house of commons 
at britains insistence foreign ministers of the 12nation 
european community will review sanctions against south africa at a 
feb 20 meeting in dublin ireland 
diplomatic sources said the netherlands and portugal also want 
to ease restrictions but ireland which holds the rotating 
sixmonth presidency of the community feels no action should be 
taken 
mrs thatcher an opponent of sanctions lifted academic and 
cultural restrictions within minutes of de klerks announcement 
friday among other things he legalized the african national 
congress guerrilla movement and promised mandela would be freed 
soon 
british opposition parties and the antiapartheid movement 
criticized her they feel sanctions should be maintained until 
apartheid is abolished 
some sanctions imposed by britain are mandatory under 
international agreements including a ban on arms exports and the 
import of south african iron steel and krugerrand gold coins 
voluntary measures could be lifted by britain unilaterally or 
after persuading some others to follow suit in the european 
community or the 49nation commonwealth the association of britain 
and its former colonies 
nonbinding measures include bans on investment and tourism 
promotion 
mrs thatcher reacted mildly to the expulsions from south africa 
earlier tuesday of two british journalists who were covering the 
tour of an unofficial english cricket team 
we have told the south african authorities that we regret 
these expulsions she said then noted that south africa said one 
was working illegally on a tourist visa and the other filed a vivid 
account of police breaking up a demonstration he had not witnessed 
before leaving johannesburg paul weaver a sports writer with 
the london newspaper today acknowledged he had not seen the 
demonstration the british news agency press association reported 
but it quoted him as saying 
i saw the bloodstains which remained after the police had used 
dogs and tear gas on demonstrators and i spoke to many people who 
were there at the time 
the other expelled journalist was gareth furby of independent 
radio news whose reports the government in pretoria said were 
intended to damage south africas image 
