<TEXT>
escalating gang violence despite increased 
arrests and prosecutions is forging an alliance between community 
groups and law enforcement participants in a state summit on gangs 
said tuesday 
educators law enforcement authorities and leaders of community 
programs were taking part in a twoday conference to fight gang 
influence in neighborhoods 
state and local law enforcement authorities who have seen death 
tolls rise from gang violence said enlisting people in 
gangplagued neighborhoods may be the only hope in fighting the 
problem 
i dont think that we can any longer assume that by putting 
more and more gang members and drug dealers into jail we are going 
to force them somehow into submission said los angeles police 
cmdr lorne kramer 
communities need to be mobilized we definitely need to 
develop more comprehensive preventative programs 
los angeles county sheriffs department figures show 554 
gangrelated homicides in the county in 1989 exceeding the record 
452 homicides in 1988 
there are an estimated 80000 gang members today in the los 
angeles area up from 30000 in 1980 said steve valdivia 
executive director of the citys antigang agency community youth 
gang services 
the conference which ends wednesday focused on training small 
community organizations to work together and with law enforcement 
in developing and expanding programs to help neighborhoods rid 
themselves of gangs 
youve got to look for some quickfix successes that you can 
take into neighborhoods said natalie salazar executive director 
of los angeles community reclamation project youve got to get 
rid of the graffiti knock down some of the crack houses in the 
area make sure the street lights are fixed make sure the streets 
are swept 
crp is a federally funded pilot program based in the harbor area 
of los angeles an area inhabited for generations by hispanic and 
filipino gangs 
salazar said the yearold program works with schools in 
antigang and antidrug education and sponsors recreational 
activities and citizens meetings with law enforcement agencies 
federal officials hope to expand the program scheduled to end 
in july to other cities and states 
working on a small scale sometimes just a twoblock area the 
program teaches how to cope with such problems as graffiti and 
loitering salazar said 
to combat the factionalism inherent in gang culture the program 
sponsored a basketball tournament that involved 500 junior high 
schoolage youths 
kids from particular neighborhoods often feel they cant go 
into other neighborhoods or learn to hate people from other 
neighborhoods she said the basketball tournament helps form 
bonds with kids from other neighborhoods 
in the los angeles police departments newton division which 
has one of the highest homicide rates of any police precinct in the 
