<TEXT>
firefighters tuesday raced to save 
about 250 nearextinct golden lion marmosets from a forest fire 
that has ravaged a wildlife reserve for rare animals in 
southeastern brazil officials said 
more than 200 firefighters police and biologists were unable to 
halt the fire which started saturday in the poco das antas 
wildlife reserve 80 miles northeast of rio said reserve director 
dionizio pessamilio 
pessamilio said the fire had burned about half the 12300acre 
reserve the last remaining natural habitat for the marmoset and a 
sanctuary for rare sloths alligators and jaguars 
the situation is bad he said in a televised interview 
the dense forest where the tamarins live is now burning 
worsening their chances of survival 
tamarin is another name for the marmoset a monkey the size of a 
cat with a lionlike mane and a bushy tail 
pessamilio said biologists had already lost contact with several 
of the creatures which are monitored by means of tiny radio 
transmitters tied around their necks 
environmentalists are concerned the fire may kill all of the shy 
animals because they hide in tree holes for warmth and shelter 
high wind difficult access to the mountainous area and a lack 
of water caused by a long dry spell hampered firefighters efforts 
pessamilio said 
only several days of heavy rain would put out the fire he said 
rain was not forecast for the region until friday 
globo tv the nations largest network showed helicopters 
airlifting firefighters to burning areas and crews battling flames 
with portable water tanks and rubber mats 
fernando mesquita president of the brazilian institute of the 
environment and renewable resources said more firefighters would 
join the effort and work aroundtheclock 
the cause of the fire was not known but officials said 
unusually dry weather and 100degree summer temperatures could have 
caused the fire to begin spontaneously 
poco das antas has become the center of an international crusade 
to protect the environment 
the reserve was founded in 1974 and funded by the smithsonian 
institution in washington the world wildlife fund and the 
brazilian and canadian environmental groups 
the marmoset first faced extinction in 1972 when just 70 
remained on earth after poachers hunters and ranchers trapped them 
and cut down their forest habitats 
but the animal slowly had been reproducing after naturalists 
released them in groups from foreign zoos into the brazilian forest 
</TEXT>
