<TEXT>
the three major republican fundraising 
committees reaped more than 80 million in 1989 and entered this 
election year with more than 14 million on hand nearly triple the 
combined war chest of their democratic counterparts the federal 
election commission said tuesday 
the democratic national committee and the partys separate house 
and senate campaign arms raised and spent more than 19 million in 
1989 and carried over 54 million to this year 
last year was an unusually costly off year because of eight 
special congressional elections but while they spent considerable 
amounts on those races the national parties focused much of their 
resources on building stronger fundraising machinery for this year 
the performance of the democratic groups while an improvement 
over past nonfederal election years was again dwarfed by that of 
the gops money machines but tempering the republican edge is the 
fact that more democrats who hold a majority in both chambers of 
congress enjoy the lopsided donor preference for giving to the 
individual campaign coffers of incumbents thus republicans with 
more challengers than incumbents are more reliant on national 
party support 
the fec data showed that the three republican committees spent 
722 million of the 804 million they took in last year 
but because of cash left over from 1988 the gop groups entered 
this year already armed with 144 million the overwhelming bulk 
of that money 106 million was in the coffers of the national 
republican senatorial committee which is hoping to erode the 
democratic majority in that chamber this year as part of a strategy 
aimed at recapturing the senate in the 1992 presidential elections 
the gop senate committee which raised 354 million and spent 
27 million reported 589734 in debts as of jan 31 about half 
its 11 million debt at the end of 1987 the last comparable 
nonelection year 
the national republican congressional committee the gops main 
fundraising arm for house candidates raised 142 million and 
spent 131 million according to its yearend filing with the fec 
the nrcc had 23 million heading into this year and debts of 
794654 up dramatically from the 34922 in red ink it reported 
two years ago 
the republican national committee meanwhile reported receiving 
306 million in 1989 and spending 31 million because of its 1988 
reserves it carried over 15 million into this year while 
reporting no debt according to the fec 
on the democratic side the democratic national committee and 
the democratic senatorial campaign committee reported significant 
strides last year in reducing debts but the partys cashpoor 
democratic congressional campaign committee nearly doubled its debt 
from two years ago and entered this year with just 22179 on hand 
the dccc said it raised 41 million last year and spent 42 
million its reported debts grew from 828889 at the end of 1987 
to 16 million as of jan 31 the 22179 it had on hand entering 
the year was less than onetenth of the nearly 233000 it held at 
the beginning of 1988 
far more impressive was the fundraising of the democratic 
senate committee which said it collected 8 million in 
contributions and other receipts and spent 6 million the 
democrats senate campaign operation had nearly 16 million in the 
bank as the year began and had sliced the 1 million debt it 
reported two years ago down to 319201 
the democratic national committee meanwhile reported receipts 
of 68 million and said it drew on 1988 reserves in spending 84 
million last year those reserves comparatively deep for the 
democratic party allowed it to enter the year with 38 million on 
hand up dramatically from the 722288 the party coffers held at 
the end of 1987 
the dnc also reported debts of 111837 at the end of last year 
down from more than 16 million in red ink reported in its 
yearend filing two years ago 
we feel very good about it and look forward to a very good 
1990 dnc treasurer robert farmer said adding the dnc hoped to 
raise at least 10 million he said national party groups will face 
competition for money because of 36 gubernatorial elections and 
other state races vital to the outcome of congressional 
redistricting 
for all of the committees the totals raised include 
contributions and other receipts such as interest on bank accounts 
and certificates of deposit 
