<TEXT>
a federal appeals court ruled tuesday that 
mississippis public universities are insufficiently desegregated 
overruling a lower court judge 
in its 21 decision the 5th us circuit court of appeals said 
that with few exceptions the states five historically white and 
three historically black universities remain virtually as 
segregated as they were when black citizens sued the state in 
january 1975 
in their majority opinion judges irving goldberg and sam d 
johnson said there were many steps but no discernible degrees of 
progress unfortunately this case lingered loitered and lulled 
for more than a decade 
the court sent the case back to us district judge neal b 
biggers jr who had dismissed the lawsuit after declaring 
mississippis university system sufficiently desegregated 
most state and university officials could not be reached 
immediately for comment and those who could were guarded in their 
comments 
i have learned about this decision secondhand i have not seen 
any legal documents im quite sure our attorneys will be briefing 
us soon said aubrey lucas president of the university of 
southern mississippi 
the appellate court ordered further proceedings involving a 
broader cast of characters 
psychologists sociologists economists engineers doctors 
and professionals from all relevant areas of learning play a 
role said the majority opinion 
windows must open to ventilate the courtroom with ideas from 
the winds of truth it said to this end testimony 
depositions crossexaminations and opinions can assist only then 
should the parties come forth with a definite plan for achieving 
desegregation 
in a dissent judge john duhe said mississippi had fulfilled its 
legal obligation to open its universities to all students 
regardless of race 
the majority relying on district and other circuit court 
decisions has imposed upon the state the same constitutional 
duty required for primary and secondary education where freedom of 
choice is unavailable and services are free of charge 
in doing so wrote duhe it takes a liberty that is simply 
not available to courts of appeals 
in its review the 5th circuit said racial imbalances of 
students faculty undergraduate and graduate programs 
appropriations and admissions policies among other things have 
continued since the court ordered the university of mississippi to 
enroll james meredith its first black student in 1962 
to this day the majority said historically white delta state 
university mississippi state university mississippi university 
for women the university of mississippi and the university of 
southern mississippi enjoy distinct advantages over historically 
black alcorn state jackson state and mississippi valley state 
universities 
standardized college admissions examinations as administered by 
mississippi also discriminate the court said and the board of 
trustees of state institutions of higher learning spent more money 
on educating students at mostly white institutions than they did on 
students at black schools 
for instance the court said the state spent an average 1351 
in 1960 and 8516 in 1986 on each student enrolled at historically 
white institutions the average at historically black schools was 
718 in 1960 and 6038 in 1986 the court said 
the badge of inferiority that marks black institutions has not 
been removed goldberg and johnson wrote as such there 
remains in mississippis higher educational system vestiges of 
discrimination which distort the perceptions of black students 
vestiges of de jure segregation permeate the public university 
system of mississippi admissions policies the racial composition 
of the faculty and administration funding practices academic 
offerings and mission designations all perpetuate a stigma of 
inferiority 
