<TEXT>
a food and drug administration survey that 
found the nations milk supply to be free of veterinary drug 
residues was attacked tuesday in a congressional hearing 
the challenges to the fda survey of milk in 14 cities came from 
rep ted weiss chairman of the house government operations 
subcommittee on government and human resources and fda scientist 
joseph settepani 
too many government officials seem to think their overriding 
responsibility is to reassure the public that the milk supply is 
safe even when it may not be said weiss dny alleging that 
fda is more concerned with public relations than science 
the fda released a study monday that contradicted findings of 
two surveys by the wall street journal and an advocacy group the 
center for science in the public interest as well as findings of 
its own 
both private tests were done using a relatively new test known 
as the charm 2 the test is highly sensitive able to test drug 
residues in amounts as low as five parts per billion its advocates 
say 
but the fda said the test yields too many false positives and 
none of its positive findings could be validated in what it 
considered to be better even newer tests the charm 2 test is 
limited also because it detects only classes of drugs not 
individual drugs within a class fda says 
the fda said that using charm 2 it found a variety of drugs in 
36 out of 70 samples of those 14 contained sulfa drugs 
those 14 were tested by high pressure liquid chromatography 
which found sulfa drugs in 11 samples that test was sensitive to 
at least 10 parts per billion 
the test has been accepted by federal regulators for detecting 
only a single drug sulfamethazine and not for the purpose it was 
used in the newest test according to fda testimony 
the 11 samples were further tested by mass spectrometry and 
none was found to be positive for individual sulfa drugs the test 
is capable of isolating specific drugs but it is less sensitive 
than charm 2 able only to detect amounts of 20 parts per billion 
six of 11 samples were below 20 parts per billion by the other 
tests 
there is just no way to believe that mass spectrometry which 
is sensitive to only about 20 parts per billion could have picked 
those up even by your expectations weiss said 
settepani who testified with the fda panel and earlier with a 
member of the consumer group complained that fda had earlier tried 
to discredit tests that find potentially dangerous residues in milk 
the initial reaction to each new report of residues in milk 
has been attempts to discredit the assay used to obtain the 
reported results he said 
he said a 1988 internal memorandum listed 30 drugs believed to 
be used by milk producers 16 of them extensively but current 
standard tests used by state inspectors can only detect two he 
said 
