baker has publicly lent support to the general idea of german 
reunification without committing himself to any specific approach 
he has stressed only that the country be in the north atlantic 
treaty organization and that it evolve in a peaceful stepbystep 
way 
his support for the genscher plan therefore could be 
significant soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze with 
whom baker will open four days of talks in moscow on wednesday 
night has called for an international referendum while expressing 
concern over the revival of sinister shadows of the past 
bakers visit to prague coincided with a visit by east german 
premier hans modrow for talks with czech premier marian calfa 
there has been speculation but no confirmation that baker and 
modrow might meet 
modrow told reporters in a noquestions briefing that he ahd 
calfa agreed that german reunification should only be completed 
in a process which respects and preserves the interests of 
neighbors and european states 
baker discussed the situation with french foreign minister 
roland dumas during a refueling stop in shannon ireland and then 
flew here for talks with leaders of czechoslovakias velvet 
revolution 
baker met with vaclav havel the dissident playwright who was 
elevated to the presidency with the disintegration of the communist 
party in december and separately with roman catholic cardinal 
frantisek tomasek and leaders of the civic forum the prodemocracy 
group that toppled the hardliners 
baker told reporters that he had a very productive 
discussion with havel about troop and weapon reductions in europe 
and that it would be resumed when havel visits washington in two 
weeks 
he announced a series of moves by the bush administration to 
assist czechoslovakias economy including the dismantling of us 
trade barriers provided laws are enacted permitting free 
elections and support for czechoslovakias entry into the 
international monetary fund the us exportimport bank 
but he cautioned the prague government that it is up to you to 
provide a conducive legal environment to turn over or sell 
factories to private owners and to lift the heavy hand of 
excessive government intervention 
he brought an offer of technical advice to assist the countrys 
adoption of a free market system and other capitalistic wrappings 
that are enticing american businesses but he brought no aid 
they do not want a handout said a us official who briefed 
reporters on condition of anonymity 
here as elsewhere in europe attention is riveted on germany 
and the future of american and soviet troops 
havel has demanded the withdrawal of the estimated 75000 soviet 
soldiers in czechoslovakia his plans for disarmament could be an 
impetus for further us cuts beyond the 100000 or so that would 
be withdrawn under president bushs latest proposal 
but a us official said there are many statements by havel 
and others in czechoslovakia who recognize an important us role 
in political economic and security terms 
baker and dumas in their 90minute meeting in ireland both 
recognized that unification is moving ahead very quickly the 
senior us official said they thought that all things 
considered that its actually moving along in a pretty effective 
fashion 
while the french foreign minister did not specifically endorse 
the genscher plan the official said from the tone of it it was 
very positive moreover the official said the 16member nato 
alliance is moving toward a consensus in support of the plan 
genscher discussed it with baker at the state department last 
friday night and it is bound to be a major item in the agenda for 
bakers talks with shevardnadze and with soviet president mikhail 
s gorbachev 
genscher has come up with one proposal and we think that the 
proposal in terms of not having nato forces move further east is a 
pretty good one the official said 
also he stressed it would keep the new and larger germany in 
nato a move that is designed to reassure other european countries 
who have suffered in two devastating wars this century 
</TEXT>
