<TEXT>
 
men dont leave 
 
beth macauley wanders catatonically through the basement web of 
a maryland hospital trying to find the morgue so she can check the 
remains of her dead husband she throws open a door and happens 
upon a bevy of chefs chopping up raw chickens and collapses into 
uncontrollable sobs 
it is this quirky blend of the ordinary the extraordinary the 
absurd and the surreal that makes paul brickmans men dont 
leave more than just another soapy look at a family tragedy 
jessica lange continues to fascinate with her range of emotions 
and faces as beth she reverts to an unexceptional housewife and 
mother whose entire existence is focused on her family when left 
with a bundle of bills after her husband dies in an explosion an 
enraged teenage son and a younger more introverted son she copes 
by leaving comfortable suburbia for the rough and crowded confines 
of baltimores inner city 
she finds work as an assistant manager a gofer really for 
a shrill neurotic who runs a gourmet food store and meets the 
understanding sensitive man her youngest son matt charlie 
korsmo takes up with a middleclass juvenile delinquent and her 
oldest son chris chris odonnell finds love in the arms of an 
allknowing allseeing amazon of an older woman jody joan 
cusack 
brickman takes us in fits and starts through the inevitable 
motherson fights and confrontations bouts of depression lessons 
in friendship loyalty and trust in the end it all works out 
beth learns acceptance and believes in herself 
but the package is not as neat as it sounds beths journey is 
all too episodic like a madefortelevision movie and there are 
too many cute pieces of business such as when she delivers a 
basket of lunch to a rehearsing orchestra and drops oranges along 
the way and finally the entire basket 
brickman seems to see middleclass america through barbed wire 
glasses and he takes marvelous risks in risky business he 
gave us an aspiring college student who earned money by turning his 
parents house into a brothel it was funny and it worked 
in men dont leave mrs average upstanding housewife learns 
to like her childs lover a woman close to her own age 
cusack is a delight as the older woman she steals the scene 
the minute she appears commanding presence that she is with her 
measured tone and wideeyed wonder 
the yougsters are fine without being cloying corey carrier as 
the juvenile thug winston buckley is carved from the same mold 
that coughed up the little rascals decades ago hes bad but hes 
cute 
brickman directed from a screenplay written by himself and 
barbara benedek the story was by benedek the brickmanjon avnet 
production is released by the geffen company and is rated pg13 
by dolores barclay ap arts editor 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
mountains of the moon 
 
when lawrence of arabia was rereleased last year in all its 
bigscreen uncut glory the cry went up why dont they make 
movies like this anymore answer they do 
mountains of the moon has all the excitement adventure and 
human conflict of lawrence of arabia while the carolco 
production may lack the polish that perfectionist david lean gave 
to his 1962 classic mountains is still firstrate movie 
storytelling 
the discovery of the source of the nile in the mid19th century 
was as clouded in controversy as the journey to the north pole a 
halfcentury later the contenders richard burton the 
largerthanlife irish adventurerauthorscientist and john speke 
an english army officer from an aristocratic family 
director bob rafelson and william harrison based the script on 
harrisons biographical novel about the two explorers as well as 
their original journals what emerges is a complex tale of two men 
of widely divergent backgrounds who become brothers on their 
perilous journey 
the african adventure is magnificently portrayed and it is 
bookended by episodes in england that are less engaging the first 
part delineates the characters of burton patrick bergin a 
dashing adventurous figure who wins the heart of a strongwilled 
english lady fiona shaw and speke iain glen a blond 
blueblooded young man who comes under the sinister influence of a 
homosexual publisher richard e grant 
the final part of the film concerns the aftermath of the 
exploration as the two comrades are torn apart by misunderstanding 
and dispute over which one should be honored by the national 
geographic society 
rafelson conveys the complicated story with admirable concision 
despite the cost some big scenes last only a few seconds just 
long enough to establish needed story points known mostly for 
intimate films such as five easy pieces and stay hungry 
rafelson displays a rare talent for the epic his battle scenes are 
extraordinary 
bergin captures all the brusque authority and zest for life of 
burton in the less showy role as speke glen is equally 
impressive fiona shaw is wise knowing and sensual as mrs burton 
the tristar release was produced by daniel melnick and bears an 
r rating presumably for brief nudity and considerable violence 
running time 135 minutes 
by bob thomas associated press writer 
</TEXT>
