<TEXT>
ashraf anjoorgar leans closer to his 
makeshift canvas to dab a more wishful shade of blue at the sky 
above the minaret of jam 
his painting shows the 900yearold monument in central ghor 
province as it looked before the damage and neglect wrought by more 
than a decade of afghanistans civil war 
ashraf works by light that filters through sandbagged windows 
at kabul universitys fine arts building there is no heat or 
electricity 
a lot of our most talented artists have left because of the 
war he said with the help of an interpreter there are many 
young artists who want to learn but there is a shortage of 
materials to teach them 
he made his canvas by stretching a piece of bed linen over a 
wooden frame there arent enough brushes paints or materials such 
as gypsum and marble for sculpture 
ashraf is an instructor and has joined about 3000 afghan 
painters sculptors musicians dramatists cinematographers and 
architects in trying to preserve their embattled countrys ancient 
art and cultural traditions 
mohammad haider pardes an architect and president of the union 
of artists associations of afghanistan says many of his members 
can earn a living only by lending their talents to the 
moscowbacked government 
the art gallery at kabul university alma mater of afghanistan 
president najib and his archrival fundamentalist rebel leader 
gulbaddin hekmatyar is a collage of pastoral landscapes 
depictions of archeological treasures portraits sculptures and 
posters 
most have mundane motifs but the posters especially bear the 
hard lines of a political exhortation to defend the homeland 
against usbacked moslem rebels they have fought for 11 years to 
topple the ruling peoples democratic party of afghanistan and 
replace it with an allislamic government 
some of our artists work for the government some of the time 
but otherwise theyre free to create whatever they want pardes 
said 
very few of our artists have formal training weve been 
sending them to the soviet union india and east european 
countries he said we are interested in preserving our 
cultural heritage but we are also trying to introduce our culture 
to others this training program helps us do both 
pardes admitted however that the fall of several communist 
governments in eastern europe has disrupted the program the army 
has too all afghan men must serve at least once the fine arts 
faculty at kabul are required to put in two years their 300 
students can look forward to four after graduation if the 
stalemated war lasts 
faculty members also must join the ruling party pardes said 
but not the students most of whom are the children of party 
members 
he said that other talented afghans either have been killed 
pressed into government service or fled the country among more than 
5 million refugees one of the countrys most renowned young 
painters works as a construction engineer 
pardes union office is carpeted and plush but as an architect 
he designs public housing blocks mosques and parks for which there 
is no money to build 
like many of kabuls 2 million people he hopes this year will 
bring some kind of peace to afghanistan 
were trying to preserve our heritage many of our finest 
monuments have been destroyed i think people dont have more 
patience with this bloody situation he said 
more than 15 million afghans a tenth of the countrys prewar 
population are believed to have died since the 1978 marxist coup 
that installed the ruling pdpa and touched off the insurgency 
soviet forces fought alongside the government for nine years but 
withdrew last february 
