<TEXT>
under the living room carpet in the 
converted barn author ken kesey calls home is a wrestling mat that 
has cushioned roughhousing with his four children and is a 
touchstone for the life he leads on his farm 
ive always been very tight with my family said kesey who 
saw both his sons follow in his footsteps as wrestlers for the 
university of oregon its always been the most important thing 
in my life 
kesey has lived on this farm since 1965 after his novels one 
flew over the cuckoos nest and sometimes a great notion won 
him literary fame his father and brother both owned it before him 
when i was working on sometimes a great notion one of the 
reasons i could do it was because i was unknown he said i 
could get all those balls in the air and keep them up there and 
nothing would come along and distract me now theres a lot of 
stuff happens that happens because im famous and famous isnt 
good for a writer you dont observe well when youre being 
observed 
many of the outbuildings on the farm were built by the merry 
pranksters he led in the psychedelic bus trip across america 
chronicled by tom wolfe in the electric koolaid acid test the 
bus called further is parked out back 
everybody in my family knows what ive done ive smoked dope 
and would still be smoking dope if i could get some kesey said 
i know enough about drugs to know that you cant really be 
a good family person and take certain types of drugs they turn you 
into yourself cocaine and the opiates any of the barbiturates 
booze those harm your family 
but the real psychedelics they increase your awareness of the 
spiritual forces around you which i think increases your love i 
dont know anybody who ever had family problems because of smoking 
marijuana they may have had financial problems because theyre too 
lazy to get up and go to work but they always like to hang around 
and play with the kids and the dogs be in the kitchen 
kesey got his first taste of lsd in the early 1960s in 
governmentrun experiments in menlo park calif where he also was 
studying writing under wallace stegner at stanford university his 
first novel one flew over the cuckoos nest was published in 
1962 
i felt like i was doing as american a thing as neil armstrong 
when he volunteered to go to the moon kesey said of the drug 
experiments there was a new place to be explored and we were 
astronauts 
that exploration of new territory is a very american thing 
say youre doing cocaine that is not exploration of new territory 
thats just a titillation 
most recently kesey has been giving performances of tricker 
the squirrel meets big double the bear a story told by his 
grandmother and set to music by a neighbor art maddox 
he figures that videotapes of writers reading their works into 
the cameras eye interspersed with actors presenting scenes will 
take the place of books his son zane has done a tricker 
piece that cuts between kesey with the orchestra and kesey 
lipsyncing in the swamp behind his home 
it will take over for about 50 or 70 years and then all that 
machinery will fall apart and well be back to the printed word 
kesey said 
kesey has taken a lot of heat for not producing another novel to 
put beside the first two but he is halfway through one now and 
under contract to finish it this year 
theres a saying from william faulkner who said every so 
often the dog has to go against the bear just to keep calling 
himself a dog the novel is the real bear 
called sailors song the book is set in a fishing village 
on the coast of southeastern alaska a little bit in the future 
when things are bleaker and more hedonistic than they are now 
i think its about love at the end of the world kesey says 
can you love when you know things are coming to an end 
the main characters are an indian woman and a cropduster who 
moves to town from fresno calif after the death of his child 
before leaving california he loads his plane from a truck that 
pumps out portable toilets and sprays the state fair 
when not working on the novel kesey is involved with his wife 
faye who was his high school sweetheart and their children 
shannon zane jed and sunshine who all grew up on the farm jed 
was buried here after his death in 1984 in the crash of a van 
carrying the university of oregon wrestling team to pullman wash 
i learned something from jeds death which is how badly it 
hurts and that if i were to die it would hurt other people and i 
dont want to hurt other people kesey said i button my seat 
belt and wear my life jacket i used to think its my life i can 
do with it what i want but its not just my life 
recently he and zane planted some trees along the property 
line at 54 kesey doesnt expect to see the trees reach maturity 
but feels they are part of the chain that is family 
kesey has a granddaughter katherine grace born to shannon 
shortly after new years day and he is angered that many americans 
doom their progeny by despoiling the environment 
it used to be that old people instead of spending their money 
at the end of their life would be passing that money on to their 
children and grandchildren kesey said but now weve been 
taught to go ahead and waste it fill the sky with poison were 
not going to be here anyway 
i have vowed not to do that this piece of land wont move out 
of this family once you bury a kid on your land it would take a 
bulldozer and a large government to move you 
kesey recalled how several years ago a busload of people 
stopped by on their way from california to kansas and asked kesey 
to come along 
they all had a vision that the whole west coast was going to 
fall in the ocean and they were all moving to kansas kesey said 
they were the messiest bunch when they finished with a can they 
just threw it peoples clothes were dirty their hair was uncut 
they were angry with us for not joining them 
they were sitting there and faye got up and came back with a 
big knife and saw i said where are you going she said im 
going to go prune the fruit trees 
thats my feeling even if it is going to fall into the ocean 
you still have got to prune the fruit trees and wash the dishes and 
take care of the daily chores of keeping the world running 
</TEXT>
