<TEXT>
women who are suddenly widowed survive the 
trauma better than men whose spouses die unexpectedly but when 
death follows lengthy illness men seem to handle things better a 
sociologist says 
studies have shown that women generally weather a spouses death 
better than men but womens traditional role as caregiver works 
against them when a death follows prolonged illness said ken smith 
of the university of utah 
the idea here is that women because they are taking on more 
caregiver burden are likely to face a higher rate of mortality 
smith said 
working with data from a multifaceted nationwide study of 5000 
married couples that began in 1968 smith studied data from 113 
widowers and 383 widows over 14 years after a spouse died and 
compared each with a control couple 
men who suddenly became widowed were 52 percent more likely to 
die within 14 years than men whose wives remained alive while men 
whose wives died after a long illness were only 13 percent more 
likely to die than nonwidowers 
women whose husbands died suddenly faced a marginal mortality 
risk 1 percent but those enduring a husbands prolonged illness 
and death were 49 percent more likely to die than nonwidows smith 
said 
he speculates that a woman more used to caregiving is better 
prepared for life after her husbands death but she takes on a far 
greater than normal burden when nursing a husband through chronic 
illness 
men whose wives die suddenly run a higher risk of dying because 
theyre unable to prepare for unexpected life alone he said men 
tend not to possess the daily living skills that help to preserve 
ones health when she dies suddenly theres a source of support 
thats suddenly gone 
however men adopt caregiver abilities when forced to take 
responsibility for nursing a spouse through chronic illness he 
said 
regardless of how sudden a wifes death said university of 
maryland psychologist leon levy men have much greater difficulty 
with bereavement they dont have the support system women do 
men are more isolated 
jean buchin an adjunct professor at city university of new york 
who conducts workshops for people whose spouses have died said 
smiths study does not consider age the age factor of the 
widowed plays an important role older widows take the impact of 
widowhood sudden or anticipated in general harder 
economically emotionally and socially than younger women 
paul costa head of the laboratory of personality and cognition 
at the national institute of aging in baltimore said his own 
findings show the acute bereavement of the first six months has 
significant effects while longterm grieving has virtually no 
impact on mortality or longterm wellbeing 
smith agrees but puts the maximum impact later you can see 
where the bereavement really kicks in things seem to peak at about 
one year 
he presented his initial findings on widowhood last summer at a 
conference of the society for epidemiologic research and is 
revising the paper for publication by the american journal of 
epidemiology 
