<TEXT>
as the state with the oldest population 
florida offers lessons on dealing with the problems of a graying 
america a demographer says 
the way florida deals with this aging population could be very 
instructive to the nation as a whole when it has to deal with it in 
the year 2020 or 2030 said stanley k smith director of 
population research with the university of floridas bureau of 
economic and business research 
those 65 and older will comprise an estimated 18 percent of 
floridas 13 million residents this year and could hit 26 percent 
by the year 2020 
an older population has a major impact on such things as 
health care child care education the labor force and voter 
participation smith said 
however the growing elderly population is not predicted to be a 
drain on floridas resources as some officials fear in fact he 
said recent studies have shown that the economic benefit of the 
elderly population far outweighs by four or five times its 
demand on the social system 
florida has a unique retiree healthier and considerably 
wealthier than the average for the united states he said 
and there also seems to be some evidence that when they start 
to become really old when they begin placing more demands on the 
social system they often move back to new york or ohio or wherever 
they migrated from 
