environmental disaster in the next century 
bushs speech to an international conference on global warming 
monday included more talk about economics than the 
environment said daniel becker of the sierra club calling the 
presidents remarks a gross disappointment 
the administration was likely to get a better reception today 
when william reilly head of the environmental protection agency 
appeared before a senate committee to endorse the creation of a 
cabinetlevel department of the environment 
while that decision is gaining bush plaudits among 
environmentalists his remarks on global warming prompted sharp 
criticism 
sen albert gore dtenn a frequent critic of the 
administrations environmental record accused the president of 
moving as slow as molasses on concerns by many scientists that 
manmade pollution accumulating in the atmosphere threatens to 
significantly warm the earth by the middle of the next century 
what were hearing is talk of another year of waiting i 
expected a lot more concern about the global warming problem 
said rafe pomerance of the world resources institute 
bush speaking to the 60nation intergovernmental panel on 
climate change said our policies must be consistent with 
economic growth he complained that in some areas of the debate 
over the greenhouse effect politics and opinion have outpaced 
the science 
our goal continues to be matching policy commitments to 
emerging scientific knowledge and a reconciling of environmental 
protection to the continued benefits of economic development the 
president said promising to convene a white house conference on 
global warming in the spring 
james tripp a lawyer for the environmental defense fund said 
bush failed to demonstrate the political will necessary to make 
the united states a leader in the effort to prevent global 
warming 
but tom lambrix head of the global climate coalition an 
industry group called bushs view of global warming an 
appropriate balance 
we need a better understanding of the economic and social 
implications of dealing with global warming said lambrix 
director of government relations for the phillips petroleum co 
the united nationssponsored conference of technical experts is 
meeting to work on a proposed treaty to deal with global warming 
reilly issued a statement saying the presidents remarks made 
clear his determination to lead the world in addressing global 
climate change 
bush does not believe it is time for a call to arms on 
global warming but instead favors continued research presidential 
spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters after the presidents 
remarks 
but many environmentalists argue there is enough scientific 
evidence to warrant a commitment from the united states and other 
industrial nations to reduce global warming gases especially 
carbon dioxide from the burning of fossil fuels 
scientists fear such an accumulation of manmade pollutants will 
act like a greenhouse trapping heat and reflecting it back to 
earth causing a warming of the globe scientists disagree on how 
severe the warming will become or its effect although some 
scientists predict droughts in some interior regions and coastal 
flooding because of higher ocean levels 
reducing greenhouse gases would require less reliance on coal 
oil and natural gas and would require industry to develop more 
energyefficient automobiles and industrial plants which industry 
fears could result in widespread economic disruption 
