<TEXT>
automakers pared their newcar inventories 
sharply last month by cutting production and offering incentives 
giving them room to boost manufacturing schedules somewhat to 
prepare for spring 
the eight major us automakers on monday reported a 15 percent 
decline in car and truck sales during late january a 66 percent 
drop in car sales during jan 2131 was offset largely by an 81 
percent increase in light truck sales 
analysts said the figures were better than they appeared because 
sales in the yearearlier period were inflated by a special factor 
during all of january when general motors corp ford motor co 
and chrysler corp shut down assembly and supplier plants for at 
least a week at a time combined car and truck sales by the eight 
domestic makers were up 62 percent from january 1989 
sales of imported cars and trucks fell 61 percent in january 
it looks like we just went from 97 days worth of supply on 
december 31 to about 65 at the end of january said analyst 
charles brady of oppenheimer amp co of new york city sales have 
run 80 percent ahead of production 
thats something ive never seen before in a january period 
he added 
automakers usually let inventories build a little in february as 
they prepare for what usually is an increased buying pace in march 
and april 
the key now is how you manage it brady said you nudge up 
production and nudge back incentives and find a happy medium 
many of the big three plants that were shut down in january are 
returning to production this month 
but in march gm and chrysler will make some permanent cuts by 
slowing line speeds eliminating shifts or in the case of gms 
atlanta assembly plant shutting down an entire factory 
indefinitely all told the two companies have announced indefinite 
layoffs that will idle about 15400 workers at 11 plants between 
january and september 
