<TEXT>
the bush administration today sent congress a 
package of recommendations for new farm legislation but did not 
spell out how commodity programs should be reduced in order to meet 
federal spending cutbacks next year 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter told a news conference the 
proposals dealt only with farm policy and did not address budget 
problems 
he said if all the proposals were approved they would have 
nominal impact on consumer food prices 
one of the most controversial items facing the administration is 
how to cut fiscal 1991 commodity spending by 15 billion a level 
included in the budget proposals president bush sent to congress 
last week 
however the budget message said only that the white house is 
prepared to work closely with lawmakers on the 15 billion 
reduction in commodity programs 
yeutter said administration policymakers do not intend to 
make specific recommendations on how to cut programs by 15 
billion but will work that out with congress when the time comes 
he is scheduled to testify before the senate agriculture committee 
on wednesday 
between 60 and 70 specific recommendations were submitted to 
congress about 90 percent of which will require legislation he 
said 
yeutter said the administrations plan calls for greater 
production flexibility and decisionmaking by farmers allowing 
them greater choice on crops to grow under annual commodity 
programs 
the package also included a recommendation for eliminating the 
departments federal crop insurance corp which provides 
subsidized allrisk coverage to farmers and replacing it with 
permanent disaster assistance 
but yeutter said the administration would listen to congress in 
case there an alternate solution is sought 
another major question is what to do with the departments 
federal crop insurance corp which provides subsidized allrisk 
coverage to farmers 
the agency has been losing money for many years with many 
farmers spurning the insurance and relying on congress to bail them 
out with emergency legislation in case of drought floods and other 
disasters 
yeutter says farmers cant have it both ways and that one or the 
other of the programs insurance or emergency aid has to go the 
bush budget recommended scrapping the insurance program in the 1991 
fiscal year that will begin oct 1 
the administration decided some time ago not to send a formally 
drafted farm bill to capitol hill to succeed the 1985 law that will 
expire at the end of the 1990 crop season instead a series 
concept papers or guidelines has been prepared 
yeutter and others have lauded the food security act of 1985 
the current farm law for helping make us commodities more 
competitive in world trade thus enhancing the nations export 
position 
the 1985 law has helped with its authority for lowering federal 
price supports and targetprice benefits due farmers the bush 
budget said there could be substantial savings if these declines 
were continued or even accelerated by the 1990 farm bill 
we must make certain that our commodity programs have enough 
flexibility to allow farmers to grow crops that consumers want 
instead of crops that the government dictates yeutter said 
monday 
this in concert with a stronger us trading stance in world 
markets for agricultural commodities and products will go a long 
way toward keeping the agrarian economy robust he told the 
national rural electric cooperative assn in orlando fla 
most major farm organizations have already taken stands on some 
of the major issues involved in 1990 farm legislation 
the american farm bureau federation for example has been a 
strong supporter of the 1985 laws emphasis on greater market 
orientation by setting price supports in line with domestic and 
global competition 
a federation position paper distributed monday called for 
maintaining the general direction set by the 1985 farm law it 
also urged greater acreage flexibility under federal commodity 
programs 
the federation said price support loan rates which act as a 
market floor for major crops such as wheat and feed grains should 
continue to be tied to a percentage of the average price of the 
commodity over the past several years 
but the federation said target prices used to compute 
deficiency payments to farmers when markets falter should be 
frozen at 1990 levels 
additional reductions would result in an unacceptable lowering 
of farm income the federation said 
the national farmers union says the 1990 farm bill should 
provide government muscle to sustain familysize farm operation 
promote environmentally safe stewardship of the land provide 
nutrition assistance for lowincome citizens and enhance the 
viability of rural communities 
generally the nfu favors supply management concepts not the 
looser marketoriented themes sought by the administration and 
the farm bureau 
for example the nfus own farm bill would tie the target price 
of wheat to the full cost of production plus a reasonable rate 
of return on a commodity base which will sustain a familysized 
unit 
</TEXT>
