<DOCNO> AP900206-0235 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
sometimes you have to watch what you say 
because people might take you too seriously 
for several years the national association of realtors has 
promoted the idea particularly through its socalled 
affordability index that houses are unaffordable for a large 
percentage of potential buyers 
the index is a product of five financial elements involved in 
owning a house the most important of them being median household 
income the median price of the typical singlefamily home and 
the level of interest rates 
if prices and interest rates rise while income remains the same 
or falls or even if income rises but not sufficiently to offset 
increases in other factors affordability is said to fall 
in december for instance the index measured 1082 up from 
1055 in november boosted to that level mainly by declines in 
mortgage rates since then rates have risen januarys index seems 
destined to fall 
its the declines that create the problems because they suggest 
that good sound american families are being denied the right to 
live as good average american families the issue is almost a 
sacred one 
never mind that at 1082 the december index meant a family 
earning the national median of 33600 had 1082 percent of income 
needed to qualify for a conventional mortgage of 80 percent on a 
home priced at 92500 
many housing people find the measure useful as a trend 
indicator but many buyers and sellers even realtors and 
sometimes the media make a different interpretation they stress 
the unaffordability aspect of the index 
the index does suggest for example that while your family 
might be close to typical in income you still might not be able to 
afford a typical house if local prices are higher than the national 
median 
it also says that millions of other american households cannot 
qualify for the typically priced house because 50 percent of them 
dont earn as much as the median income when the index falls that 
aspect is heavily stressed 
in the past in fact it was stressed very heavily by the 
realtors especially when issues affecting housing were discussed 
in washington and particularly when the index dropped below 100 
as in 1983 and 1984 
at times the unaffordability of housing was promoted by various 
housing and real estate groups as a national disgrace as something 
that demanded immediate correction perhaps through the tax system 
other groups have since picked up the cry and the issue of 
affordable housing is a huge one now and generally the stress 
is on the lack of affordable housing it is a widespread 
perception often accepted uncritically 
many americans who otherwise feel typical now are convinced 
housing is beyond their financial reach some have become market 
dropouts ignoring the fact that thousands of houses are available 
for under the typical price 
in response a grass roots campaign has begun in the northeast 
where prices are relatively high and the unaffordability attitude 
is entrenched its called yes you can meaning yes you can 
buy a home 
it seems destined to spread it originated in springfield mass 
in 1982 when high interest rates undermined the market big 
inventories convinced the greater springfield association of 
realtors to resurrect the campaign in 1989 
iy has now been adopted in new jersey where the state 
association says it plans to spend 250000 in the media and on 
billboards to promote its own campaign yes you can buy a house 
in new jersey 
in the realtors national trade paper realtor news which 
carries the index a member states that the industry has to change 
consumer perceptions about unaffordability 
the member explained that many are not hearing from the press 
that affordable homes and financing are available 
</TEXT>
