<TEXT>
the interim government on tuesday 
announced a sharp devaluation of the lei and set a single exchange 
rate aimed at better reflecting the currencys real value and 
helping repair decades of chaotic monetary policies 
the devaluation also was aimed at spurring exports by making 
romanian products relatively cheaper in foreign markets 
the ruling executive bureau of the national salvation front set 
new exchange rates against hard currencies pegged to a dollar rate 
of 21 lei 
the previous rates were 874 lei to the dollar for 
noncommercial transactions and 1423 lei for commercial 
transactions 
however the official rate remains below black market dollar 
rates now averaging about 80 lei 
the currency decree dated feb 1 was not published until 
tuesday when the new list of exchange rates appeared in the 
newspaper romania libera the decree said it was aimed at 
rectifying an abnormal situation and making the leis value 
more realistic 
the devaluation was announced less than 24 hours after the 
executive bureau which has been running the country since dictator 
nicolae ceausescu was toppled dec 22 issued another decree 
legalizing free enterprise on a much larger scale than existed 
during 45 years of communist rule 
the decree the most farreaching consumeroriented measure 
since decembers revolution will allow the existence of 
profitmaking businesses with up to 20 employees under the old 
system tradesmen could employ only up to three people and taxes 
were punitive 
under ceausescu the dollarlei exchange rate was set 
artificially high in favor of the lei in an apparent attempt to 
have it reflect what the dictator touted as romanias economic 
strength 
the single exchange rate that will replace the previous multiple 
lei rates will be set weekly by the national bank of romania to 
reflect the dollars value on international markets 
the lei rate for other hard currencies will be determined by 
their rate in relation to the dollar for example the west german 
marks rate has increased from 517 lei at the end of january to 
1250 lei starting feb 1 as that currency has strengthened 
against the dollar 
the new decree does not apply to soviet rubles or other 
nonfreely convertible currencies from countries that have 
established bilateral or multilateral agreements with fixed lei 
rates 
the new rates are expected to stimulate exports but imports 
will be more expensive in lei so the government has created a 
special fund to meet the increased cost the newspaper said 
what is important is that internal prices for consumer goods 
will not be changed tourism is thus stimulated the paper said 
</TEXT>
