<TEXT>
opec slashed oil production last month 
but not enough to meet its promised goal according to estimates 
released tuesday 
the international energy agency said in its monthly oil market 
report that the 13 opec nations produced about 233 million barrels 
of crude oil a day in january that was about 00000 barrels below 
decembers peak levels but still well above the 22millionbarrel 
limit opec pledged late last year 
the bulk of the reduction occurred in saudi arabia kuwait and 
the united arab emirates the report said 
the ministers of the organization of petroleum exporting 
countries pledged last november to cut daily production to 22 
million barrels for the first half of 1990 although the ceiling 
was 205 million barrels a day in the final quarter of 1989 actual 
production had reached 24 million barrels a day in december boosted 
by excess flow from saudi arabia kuwait and the united arab 
emirates 
analysts had expected the producing nations to rein in 
production even more in january to try to meet the new production 
cap 
nonetheless the continued brisk flow has not depressed prices 
as some had predicted world oil prices in fact soared early in 
january although they have eased slightly since then 
the average price of a basket of crudes monitored by opec was 
1956 a barrel in the last week of january down from 2046 in 
the first week of the month opecs target price is 18 a barrel 
on the futures market west texas intermediate the benchmark 
us crude has been trading in the range of 22 to 23 a barrel 
higher than the 20 to 21 range in december 
although opecs crude oil output in january has been well 
above the expectations based on the new production ceilings set by 
opec the oil market has not yet shown any significant indications 
of oversupply said the energy agency report 
analysts suggested opec production might even increase 
nick antill analyst at the london firm of county natwest said 
he had a strong suspicion that this months output would show 
little change from january he said there has been no serious 
effort to cut back on production 
pierre terzian editor of the parisbased newsletter 
petrostrategies predicted production would be higher in february 
it is increasing that is undeniable he said 
some analysts believe key producing countries want to keep 
prices around the 18 mark partly to discourage nonopec countries 
from muscling in on their share of the world oil market higher 
prices could attract more producers lower production would likely 
drive up prices some argue given the strong demand conversely 
strong production would tend to weaken them 
the energy agency estimated demand for opec oil would shrink 
from an estimated 227 million barrels a day in the first quarter 
of this year to 198 million barrels in the second three months 
total world demand was estimated at 539 million barrels a day 
in the januarymarch period and 51 million barrels in the 
apriljune period 
the report estimated production by saudi arabia the worlds 
largest crude oil exporter at 53 million barrels a day last 
month in line with its individual output quota for the first half 
of the year 
production by the united arab emirates was estimated at 2 
million barrels a day in january over its cap of 11 million 
barrels kuwaits output was recorded at 17 million barrels above 
its limit of 15 million barrels in december output was put at 
23 million barrels for the uae and 2 million barrels for kuwait 
the agency set irans supply at 29 million barrels a day in 
january and iraqs at 31 million barrels a day each has a quota 
of 31 million barrels 
other estimates for january production were qatar 400000 
barrels a day nigeria 18 million barrels libya 12 million 
barrels algeria 800000 barrels gabon 200000 barrels 
venezuela 19 million barrels ecuador 300000 barrels and 
indonesia 13 million barrels 
the international energy agency is an arm of the organization 
for economic cooperation and development made up of 24 western 
nations 
