<TEXT>
eastman kodak co on tuesday announced a 
loss of 60 million for the final quarter of 1989 due mainly to 
the costs of a restructuring the photographic company began earlier 
in the year 
the loss marked only the third time in kodaks history that it 
has reported red ink 
company officials and industry analysts cautiously predicted 
improved earnings in 1990 as kodak begins to realize savings from 
the restructuring 
the loss which amounted to 19 cents per share compared with 
earnings of 312 million or 96 cents per share in the fourth 
quarter of 1988 
sales for the fourth quarter totaled 489 billion up 8 percent 
from 454 billion in the 1988 period 
fourthquarter earnings were reduced by restructuring charges of 
322 million or 525 million before taxes bringing total charges 
for 1989 to 549 million or 875 million before taxes 
as part of the restructuring kodak sold or consolidated about 
20 businesses and eliminated 7500 jobs during 1989 in united 
states and abroad most through voluntary separation attrition and 
transfers to other businesses 
kodaks earnings for all of 1989 declined 62 percent to 529 
million or 163 per share compared with 140 billion or 431 
per share in 1988 
sales for the year totaled 184 billion up 8 percent from 
1793 billion in 1988 
clearly 1989 was a difficult year for kodak with significant 
expenses related to our restructuring efforts as the most visible 
sign kodak chairman colby h chandler said in a statement 
earnings were further restrained by the impact of general 
inflation on operating costs higher interest expense and the 
unfavorable impact of exchangerate fluctuations he said 
all segments of the company reported increases in quarterly and 
annual sales but information systems earnings dropped for both the 
quarter and the year even without the restructuring costs and 
quarterly earnings from chemical sales also sagged 
quarterly earnings in the health segment which includes 
sterling drug inc increased 15 percent without restructuring 
costs but dropped 9 percent for the year 
without the restructuring costs total kodak quarterly earnings 
would have been 262 million or 80 cents per share down 16 
percent from last year while annual earnings for the year would 
have declined 23 percent to 108 billion or 332 per share 
mark obenzinger an industry analyst with trinity trading co of 
new york said kodak expects to save 450 million to 500 million 
from the restructuring last year those savings should start to 
appear in mid1990 he said but the company will continue to face 
competitive and financial pressures 
theyll have to do even better than that in 1990 and set up a 
momentum that continues into 1991 obenzinger said 
analyst brenda landry of morgan stanley said she thought kodak 
would only manage to save about 350 million landry said she was 
revising her estimate for kodaks 1990 earnings downward from 420 
per share to around 370 or 375 
health care profits will be lower than anticipated and the 
chemical business we know will be falling apart she said 
chandler said he expects things to improve for kodak in 1990 
we look forward to higher sales better earnings from 
operations and improved cash flows especially in later quarters 
when the benefits of initiatives put into place are more fully 
realized he said 
but chandler warned that uncertainties in the us economy 
the down cycle in the chemical industry and a softening in the 
domestic market for office equipment could restrain somewhat 
the gains which might otherwise have been achieved 
the company has had a troubled decade laying off thousands of 
workers in 1983 1986 and 1989 in efforts to turn around sagging 
profits 
the two previous losses recorded by kodak also resulted from 
special charges in 1985 when the company gave up its instant 
photography business and in 1986 when more than 10000 workers were 
laid off in an earlier restructuring 
</TEXT>
