hallmark cards inc on tuesday began an 
offer to buy back at a discount some 270 million in debt 
securities used to finance univision holdings inc under a plan to 
ease the debt burden on the unprofitable spanishlanguage 
broadcaster 
the action by hallmark which owns a 635 percent stake in 
univision followed univisions failure to make 10 million in 
interest payments due last week on some of the debt 
univision the nations largest spanishlanguage communications 
company said it missed the payments because of insufficient cash 
flow 
hallmark issued a statement saying it also was seeking 
concessions on some 315 million in bank loans including a revised 
repayment schedule and increased availability of money 
hallmark which is privately held declined to comment further 
about the offer and referred all questions to thomas m daly jr of 
kekst and co a new york public relations firm daly would not say 
why hallmark was making the offer 
univision owns eight fullpower spanishlanguage television 
stations and the spanishlanguage network univision which has more 
than 500 affiliates 
the company reported a net loss of 316 million for the year 
ended dec 31 1988 the latest annual figures available it had 
1988 revenue of 132 million 
hallmark and a unit of the banking concern first chicago corp 
began their interest in the spanishlanguage communications network 
by acquiring five spanishlanguage stations in 1987 
first chicago now owns 215 percent of univision while hallmark 
owns a 635 percent stake the rest 15 percent is owned by trusts 
of descendants of univisions former owners 
hallmark said it planned to buy back two series of univision 
debt securities offering 30 cents on the dollar for one issue with 
a face value of 105 million and 45 cents on the dollar for a 
second issue with a face value of 165 million 
the original proceeds of those securities issued in july 1988 
were used to repay two loans supplied by hallmark for univision 
acquisitions 
hallmark also said that if the debt restructuring was completed 
it would defer for five years the interest payments due on both 
debt securities 
hallmark also is seeking unspecified concessions from first 
chicago the wall street journal quoted people it said were close 
to the debt negotiations as saying that first chicagos stake in 
univision would be reduced in return for improved prospects that it 
would recoup its investment 
moodys investors service inc and the standard amp poors corp 
two new york rating services lowered their credit ratings on both 
univision debt securities last friday 
