to his radio office to use a phone 
i overheard the commander saying i smelled alcohol on his 
breath i want a technician out here roberson recalled 
blood tests on hazelwood taken 10 hours after the tanker ran 
aground showed a bloodalcohol ratio of 061 lower than alaskas 
limit for a driver to be considered legally intoxicated but above 
the federal limit for operating a commercial vessel 
superior court judge karl johnstone suggested out of the jurys 
presence that attorneys were failing to address a critical issue 
whether there was liquor aboard the exxon valdez that night if no 
liquor was found he said it would mean that hazelwoods 
bloodalcohol level might have been much higher earlier in the 
evening 
roberson however was the third crewman to attest that 
hazelwood was sober and clearly in control of the ship and showed 
no signs of drunkeness 
i would describe him as serious calm said roberson who had 
seen hazelwood drinking at a valdez bar earlier in the day 
roberson was preceded on the stand by a marine pilot who 
testified that there was a telltale trace of liquor on hazelwoods 
breath but said the captains judgment seemed unimpaired an hour 
before the tanker hit bligh reef and spilled nearly 11 million 
gallons of crude oil in prince william sound 
the two crew members testimony challenged the prosecutions 
theory that hazelwood had been drinking all day and was not in 
control when the tanker foundered on bligh reef 
under crossexamination by hazelwoods attorney pilot william 
e murphy told jurors he saw none of the usual signs of 
intoxication in the captain when murphy left the ship shortly 
before it ran aground 
did you see anything that indicated the captain was impaired 
in any way asked defense attorney michael chelos 
not at all murphy replied firmly 
murphy said hazelwoods speech was not slurred he also answered 
negatively when asked if hazelwoods movements changed if his eyes 
were watery and if he had a mood change from that afternoon when 
the men had a nonalcoholic lunch together 
he seemed the same to me murphy said 
he added that he observed hazelwood giving orders to his crew 
which seemed clear and seemed in command of his ship 
when questioned monday murphy said he smelled alcohol on 
hazelwoods breath hours before the exxon valdez ran aground 
earlier in the day johnstone refused to let jurors hear about a 
grounding incident a couple months later involving murphy 
in a brief hearing outside the jurys presence murphy said the 
boat which carried 13 schoolchildren ended its journey safely 
because i drove it up on the beach 
murphy acknowledged that even the best mariners occasionally run 
aground but johnstone refused to let jurors hear that saying 
the fact that other mariners may have grounded vessels is not 
probative in this case 
he also declined to let jurors consider the impact of the 
accident on murphys testimony 
on monday murphy recalled joining hazelwood and two other crew 
members for lunch in valdez where their tanker had picked up its 
cargo of oil last march 
after lunch he said he dropped off the captain across the 
street from a bar called the pipeline club and when he next saw 
hazelwood aboard the exxon valdez about eight hours later there 
was the smell of alcohol about him 
while on the bridge did you notice any signs that he had been 
drinking assistant district attorney brent cole asked 
no replied murphy except i smelled something i 
associated with alcohol on his breath 
within 30 minutes he said hazelwood had gone below and 
remained there about an hour while murphy checked the weather 
facing the ship in its tricky passage through the valdez narrows 
its not unusual for masters to leave the bridge said 
murphy but added it wasnt typical to be gone for that long in 
the narrows 
cole had maintained in his opening statement that hazelwood was 
drunk and absent from his post when the tanker crashed onto the 
reef and said hazelwood spent the seven hours before the trip in a 
bar ordering vodka 
hazelwood is on trial on a felony charge of seconddegree 
mischief and misdemeanor charges of reckless endangerment 
negligent discharge of oil and operating a vessel while 
intoxicated the maximum penalty for conviction on all counts is 
seven years three months in prison and 61000 in fines 
to prove criminal mischief the state must show that hazelwood 
recklessly created a risk of damage to the property of another in 
excess of 100000 
under rules at the time of the exxon valdez accident pilots 
were required to guide outbound ships to a point just short of 
bligh reef 
the rules have been changed to require pilots local boat 
handlers familiar with coastal waters to remain aboard past bligh 
reef 
